<DOC><DOCNO> AP890317-0227 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-89 1016EST</FILEID><FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet10am     03-17 0384</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0403</SECOND><BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE><BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A new inflation shock rocked Wall Street today,driving stock prices into a steep decline.   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials plunged 49.28 points to2,291.43 in the first half hour of trading.   Declining issues overwhelmed advances by about 9 to 1 innationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with108 up, 914 down and 303 unchanged.   Volume on the Big Board reached 73.63 million shares as of 10a.m. on Wall Street.   The government reported this morning that the producer priceindex of finished goods rose a full percentage point in February,matching its increase the month before.   That news came as a rude surprise to stock traders, who had beenexpecting a gain of about half that size, and set off a new wave ofinflation and interest-rate worries.   In the credit markets, prices of long-term government bonds,which move in the opposite direction from interest rates, tumbledabout $17.50 for each $1,000 in face value.   Conjecture immediately began to spread in the financial worldthat the Federal Reserve would feel compelled to take further stepssoon to tighten credit in its effort to keep inflatin restrained.   The intensity of activity in the stock market was heightened bythe so-called ``triple witching hour,'' a quarterly occasion whenthe last trading occurs in a set of expiring options and futures onstock indexes.   This situation prompts heavy trading by professionals engaged incomputer program strategies that involve both the options andfutures and individual stocks.   Point-plus losers among the blue chips included Merck, down 1| at64{; USX, down 1\ at 31|; Ford Motor, down 1{ at 49|; Exxon, down 1[at 45, and General Electric, down 1\ at 45\.   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell3.32 to 164.78. At the American Stock Exchange, the market valueindex was down 3.65 at 328.87.   On Thursday the Dow Jones industrial average had climbed 20.17 to2,340.71, its highest close since it stood at 2,343.21 on Feb. 8.   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 9 to 5 on theNYSE, with 921 up, 510 down and 509 unchanged.   Big Board volume totaled 196.04 million shares, against 167.07million in the previous session.</TEXT></DOC>